body:
Hi!

I have a code:
```
module arithmetic_right_shift_of_N_by_S_using_for_inside_generate
#(parameter N = 8, S = 3)
(
  input  [N - 1:0] a, 
  output [N - 1:0] res
);

  wire signed [N - 1:0] a_s = a;
  
  genvar i;

  // Bad version
  generate
    for (i = N - 1; i > -1; i --)
      assign res[i] = i > (N - 1 - S) ? a_s[N - 1]
                                      : a_s[i + S] ;
  endgenerate

 //True version

  /*
   generate
      for (i = 0; i < N; i ++)
        if (i >= N - S)
          assign res [i] = a_s[N - 1];
        else
          assign res [i] = a_s[i + S];
    endgenerate
  */
  
endmodule
```
According to the Verilog-2001 standard, all "genvar" variables are unsigned.
They cannot take negative values, but iverilog successfully compiles the module, although it should give an error. 
Also, according to a friend, I know that iverilog can sometimes hang.
Full file with testbench you can see in: https://github.com/cfcfty/verilog_test/blob/main/p017_arithmetic_shift_or_signed_divide_by_power_of_2.v
I use IVerilog 11.0 stable on Linux and setting ` -g2005-sv `.

Thanks.

